notes: Assistant Professor at Harvard SEAS. PhD from MIT (Ankur Moitra). Member of Harvard Theory of Computation, ML Foundations, and Quantum Initiative. Research bridges theoretical CS, generative modeling, and quantum information.

name: Simran Khanuja
achievements: [Academic Research] EMNLP 2024 Best Paper for 'An Image Speaks a Thousand Words, but Can Everyone Listen?'. MIT EECS Rising Star. Rising Star in AI (UMich). BITS 30 Under 30. CMU Waibel Presidential Fellowship.
notes: PhD student at CMU Language Technologies Institute. Research on cultural inclusivity in multimodal AI and image transcreation. Advised by Graham Neubig. Multiple rising star recognitions indicate early-career leader in multilingual/multicultural AI.
currentActivity: PhD student at CMU, researching cultural AI inclusivity

name: Vaishnavh Nagarajan
achievements: [Academic Research] ICML 2025 Outstanding Paper for 'Roll the dice & look before you leap: Going beyond the creative limits of next-token prediction'. Demonstrated fundamental creative limitations of autoregressive models.
notes: Researcher who identified that next-token prediction has inherent creative limitations, contributing to the theoretical understanding of where current LLM architectures fall short. Co-authored with researchers from CMU and others.
currentActivity: Research on LLM generation theory and creative AI

name: Hannah Rose Kirk
achievements: [Academic Research] NeurIPS 2024 Best Paper (Datasets & Benchmarks) for 'The PRISM Alignment Dataset'. Revealed insights about subjective and multicultural alignment of LLMs through participatory feedback.
notes: Researcher at University of Oxford. Lead author of PRISM dataset which provides representative and individualized human feedback for LLM alignment. Challenges the assumption that one-size-fits-all alignment works across cultures.
currentActivity: Researcher at Oxford on multicultural AI alignment

name: Gautam Kamath
achievements: [Academic Research] ICML 2024 Best Paper for 'Considerations for Differentially Private Learning with Large-Scale Public Pretraining'. Leading researcher in differential privacy for ML.
notes: Professor at University of Waterloo. Co-authored with Florian Tramer (ETH Zurich) and Nicholas Carlini (Google DeepMind). Foundational work on how to properly combine public pretraining with private fine-tuning.
currentActivity: Professor at University of Waterloo, research on privacy-preserving ML

name: Dora Zhao
achievements: [Academic Research] ICML 2024 Best Paper for 'Position: Measure Dataset Diversity, Don't Just Claim It'. Developed rigorous methodology for measuring dataset diversity in ML.
notes: Researcher challenging superficial diversity claims in ML datasets. Work provides concrete measurement frameworks rather than vague diversity assertions. Co-authored with Jerone Andrews, Orestis Papakyriakopoulos, and Alice Xiang.
currentActivity: Research on dataset diversity measurement and responsible AI

name: Kulin Shah
achievements: [Academic Research] ICML 2025 Outstanding Paper co-author for 'Train for the Worst, Plan for the Best: Understanding Token Ordering in Masked Diffusions'. Demonstrated adaptive token decoding significantly enhances masked diffusion models.
notes: PhD student at UT Austin, advised by IFML Director Adam Klivans. Co-first author on ICML 2025 Outstanding Paper. Research spans machine learning theory, diffusion models, and generative modeling.

name: Derek Lim
achievements: [Academic Research] ICML 2024 Best Paper for 'The Empirical Impact of Neural Parameter Symmetries, or Lack Thereof'. Co-authored with Stefanie Jegelka and Haggai Maron.
notes: Researcher studying the role of symmetries in neural network parameters. Work provides empirical evidence on how parameter symmetries affect model training and performance, bridging theory and practice.
currentActivity: Research on neural network symmetries and equivariance

name: Xiaojuan Qi
achievements: [Academic Research] IEEE AI's 10 to Watch 2024. Research on 3D scene understanding, point cloud processing, and multimodal learning.
notes: Professor at University of Hong Kong. Recognized by IEEE as emerging AI leader. Research on 3D computer vision and embodied AI.
currentActivity: Professor at HKU, research on 3D vision and embodied AI

name: Junchi Yan
achievements: [Academic Research] IEEE AI's 10 to Watch 2024. Research on combinatorial optimization with deep learning, graph matching, and AI for science.
notes: Professor at Shanghai Jiao Tong University. IEEE recognition for emerging leadership in AI. Research on using deep learning to solve combinatorial optimization problems.

name: Emmanuel Abbe
achievements: [Academic Research] ICML 2023 Outstanding Paper for 'Generalization on the Unseen, Logic Reasoning and Degree Curriculum'. Professor at EPFL and researcher at Apple.
notes: Professor at EPFL, Switzerland and researcher at Apple. Work on understanding how neural networks generalize to unseen data through curriculum learning and logic reasoning. Bridges information theory and machine learning.
currentActivity: Professor at EPFL, researcher at Apple

name: Bohang Zhang
achievements: [Academic Research] ICLR 2023 Outstanding Paper for 'Rethinking the Expressive Power of GNNs via Graph Biconnectivity'. ICLR 2024 Outstanding Paper Honorable Mention. CAAI Outstanding Doctoral Dissertation Honorable Mention.
notes: PhD from Peking University, advised by Liwei Wang and Di He. Undergraduate from Xi'an Jiaotong University School of the Gifted Young. Research on theoretical foundations of neural networks - expressive power, robustness, and optimization.
currentActivity: Post-PhD research, continuing work on ML theory and GNN foundations

name: Junfeng Fang
achievements: [Academic Research] ICLR 2025 Outstanding Paper for 'AlphaEdit: Null-Space Constrained Knowledge Editing for Language Models'. Boosted performance of model editing methods by 36.7% average with a single line of code.
notes: Researcher at University of Science and Technology of China (USTC). Co-authored with researchers from NUS. AlphaEdit provides an elegant null-space projection approach to knowledge editing that preserves existing knowledge.

name: Yizhou Liu
achievements: [Academic Research] NeurIPS 2025 Best Paper Runner-Up for first-principles derivation of neural scaling laws robust to data distribution. Co-authored with Ziming Liu and Jeff Gore.
notes: Researcher providing theoretical foundations for neural scaling laws. Work is important because it derives scaling laws from first principles rather than empirical fitting, making predictions more robust across different data distributions.
